Note:
LINUX RISC-V 64-bit (lp64) THREADING - native syscall implementation

Implements the 33-proc threading API for Linux running on RISC-V 64-bit (rv64,
lp64 ABI) using direct __NR_clone / futex / nanosleep / gettid / sched_yield
/ prctl / sched_getaffinity syscalls per the Linux asm-generic numbering. No
pthread library, no libc -- every primitive bottoms out at the `ecall`
instruction.

Syscall numbers (Linux asm-generic, shared by rv64/rv32/arm64):
  __NR_clone               = 220
  __NR_exit                = 93     (per-thread exit)
  __NR_exit_group          = 94     (whole-process exit; unused here)
  __NR_mmap                = 222    (routed via syscall_mmap dispatcher)
  __NR_munmap              = 215    (routed via syscall_munmap dispatcher)
  __NR_futex               = 98
  __NR_gettid              = 178
  __NR_sched_yield         = 124
  __NR_nanosleep           = 101
  __NR_prctl               = 167
  __NR_sched_getaffinity   = 123

Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h in the Linux kernel source.
RISC-V uses the asm-generic table verbatim (arch/riscv/include/uapi/asm/
unistd.h is a thin wrapper that re-exports asm-generic).

The thread_create primitive uses an inline-assembly clone trampoline matching
the linux_arm64 design, but expressed in RISC-V lp64 / `ecall` mechanics.
All locking primitives use the FUTEX_WAIT / FUTEX_WAKE protocol identical
to arm64/x86_64 -- the syscall number (98) is the same as arm64 since both
use the asm-generic table; only the underlying syscall_N dispatch (via
`ecall` instead of `svc #0`) differs.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD CREATION
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_create" takes function_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a new POSIX-style thread on Linux/RISC-V 64-bit using the
    __NR_clone (220) syscall directly. We bypass libc/pthread entirely so
    the Runa runtime has no external dependency for thread spawning.

    The contract is identical to the arm64 and x86_64 siblings: returns the
    child TID (positive) in the parent on success, a negative errno on
    failure. The child never returns from this function -- it pops
    [function_ptr, arg_ptr] off its fresh stack, calls function_ptr(arg_ptr)
    with the argument in A0 (RISC-V lp64 first-arg register), and on
    user-function return invokes __NR_exit (93) so the thread tears down
    cleanly without re-entering the parent's stack frame.

    The CLONE_* flag set replicates POSIX-thread semantics (shared address
    space, shared FDs, shared signal handlers, same thread group, shared
    SysV SEM_UNDO):
      CLONE_VM       0x00000100
      CLONE_FS       0x00000200
      CLONE_FILES    0x00000400
      CLONE_SIGHAND  0x00000800
      CLONE_THREAD   0x00010000
      CLONE_SYSVSEM  0x00040000
    Sum = 0x00050F00 = 331520 (decimal). This intentionally matches the
    arm64 and x86_64 flag sets bit-for-bit so cross-platform thread
    behavior is indistinguishable from a Runa caller's perspective.

    Stack: we mmap an 8 KiB anonymous region (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
    MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS). The top of that region is seeded with
    [function_ptr, arg_ptr] (function_ptr at stack_top-8, arg_ptr at
    stack_top-16). The child's SP on entry will point at stack_top-16
    (so the first post-clone `ld` pops arg_ptr, the second pops
    function_ptr -- same convention as the arm64/x86_64 siblings).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-phase implementation:
      Phase 1 (Runa-level): mmap an 8 KiB stack; seed top with function_ptr
      and arg_ptr via memory_set_int64; compute child_sp = stack_top - 16;
      compute flags = 331520.

      Phase 2 (inline-asm): a single Inline Assembly block performs the
      clone and the in-child trampoline atomically:
        1. li   a7, 220            ; __NR_clone (asm-generic)
        2. ld   a0, -56(s0)        ; A0 = flags
        3. ld   a1, -48(s0)        ; A1 = child_sp
        4. li   a2, 0              ; A2 = parent_tid_ptr (NULL)
        5. li   a3, 0              ; A3 = tls (NULL)
        6. li   a4, 0              ; A4 = child_tid_ptr (NULL)
        7. ecall                   ; invoke syscall
        After ecall, A0 = child TID in parent, A0 = 0 in child, A0 = -errno
        on failure.
        8. bnez a0, 1f             ; if A0 != 0 (parent path or error), skip
        9. ld   a0, 0(sp)          ; child: A0 = arg_ptr (first arg)
        10. addi sp, sp, 8         ; bump SP past arg_ptr (lp64: 8 bytes)
        11. ld   t0, 0(sp)         ; T0 = function_ptr
        12. addi sp, sp, 8         ; bump SP past function_ptr
        13. jalr t0                ; jump+link via T0; call function_ptr(A0=arg_ptr)
        14. li   a0, 0             ; child: exit status = 0
        15. li   a7, 93            ; child: __NR_exit (asm-generic)
        16. ecall                  ; child: terminate this thread
        17. 1:                     ; parent path / error return label
        18. sd   a0, -64(s0)       ; result <- A0 (TID or -errno)

    Frame offset rationale: local variables are allocated in declaration
    order; the codegen layout for this Process is identical to the arm64
    sibling -- function_ptr at -8, arg_ptr at -16, stack_size at -24, stack
    at -32, stack_top at -40, child_sp at -48, flags at -56, result at -64.
    The -56 / -48 / -64 references in the inline-asm match this layout.
    RISC-V's frame pointer (when used) is S0/FP (x8); the codegen emits
    the standard prologue that establishes S0 = entry SP.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    - 8 KiB stack (vs x86_64's 64 KiB): RISC-V user code uses fewer
      push/pop slots due to the 31 general-purpose registers; deep call
      chains have headroom even at 8 KiB. Callers needing deeper stacks
      must allocate a larger pre-thread region externally.
    - Direct syscall avoids the ~150 ns libc/pthread setup cost on glibc.
    - The inline-asm trampoline is leaf-only (no spill, no frame setup)
      so the post-clone path executes in ~6 instructions before reaching
      user code. The extra instruction vs arm64 reflects RISC-V's lack
      of a post-indexed addressing mode on `ld`; the two `addi` bumps
      are needed to advance SP.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    - The new thread shares the parent's address space, FDs, and signal
      handlers (CLONE_VM|CLONE_FILES|CLONE_SIGHAND). Sandboxed callers
      must apply seccomp/landlock filters in the parent BEFORE invoking
      thread_create, since the child inherits the parent's filter state.
    - The child's stack is mmap-allocated with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE only
      (no PROT_EXEC) -- W^X is enforced; the child cannot execute code
      from its own stack.
    - On exit the thread's stack remains mapped (the parent's thread_join
      is expected to clean it up via munmap); this is a deliberate choice
      to keep the per-thread teardown atomic.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Allocate 8 KiB stack for the new thread (mmap MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE).
    Let stack_size be 8192
    Let stack be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, stack_size, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If stack is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: stack_top is the upper bound (highest addr) of the mapped region. Stack grows downward from here.
    Let stack_top be stack plus stack_size

    Note:
    Seed child stack with [function_ptr, arg_ptr] so the post-clone child
    can ld them into T0 and A0 in two loads (with addi bumps). Layout:
      stack_top - 8  = function_ptr  (popped second into T0)
      stack_top - 16 = arg_ptr       (popped first into A0 = lp64 arg)
    Child's SP on entry will be stack_top - 16.
    :End Note
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with stack_top, -8, function_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with stack_top, -16, arg_ptr

    Let child_sp be stack_top minus 16
    Let flags be 331520
    Let result be 0

    Inline Assembly att:
        # RISC-V lp64 clone() + child trampoline. The "att" dialect qualifier
        # tells Runa's codegen to emit this block verbatim (no .intel_syntax
        # noprefix / .att_syntax prefix wrappers). The block contains pure
        # RISC-V mnemonics for the riscv64 GNU assembler to consume when
        # this file is targeted at a riscv64 backend. On the current x86_64-
        # only codegen, this file is parsed and emitted but not currently
        # routed to a riscv64 assembler -- that handoff lands when the
        # riscv64 backend comes online (see Open Question 3 in P2-B design).
        #
        # Frame layout (allocation order = declaration order):
        #   function_ptr -> s0 - 8
        #   arg_ptr      -> s0 - 16
        #   stack_size   -> s0 - 24
        #   stack        -> s0 - 32
        #   stack_top    -> s0 - 40
        #   child_sp     -> s0 - 48
        #   flags        -> s0 - 56
        #   result       -> s0 - 64

        # Load syscall args into RISC-V syscall registers (A7 = syscall_num,
        # A0..A5 = args 1..6). The `ecall` instruction transitions to
        # supervisor mode and dispatches via the kernel's syscall table.
        li      a7, 220             # __NR_clone (asm-generic)
        ld      a0, -56(s0)         # A0 = flags         (clone arg 1)
        ld      a1, -48(s0)         # A1 = child_sp      (clone arg 2)
        li      a2, 0               # A2 = parent_tid_ptr (NULL)
        li      a3, 0               # A3 = tls           (NULL)
        li      a4, 0               # A4 = child_tid_ptr (NULL)
        ecall                       # invoke clone()

        # After ecall: parent has A0 = child TID, child has A0 = 0, errors are -errno
        bnez    a0, 1f              # if A0 != 0, skip child path

        # ===== Child path =====
        # Child's SP points at stack_top - 16; pop arg_ptr then function_ptr.
        ld      a0, 0(sp)           # A0 = arg_ptr               (first arg)
        addi    sp, sp, 8           # bump SP past arg_ptr (lp64: 8 bytes)
        ld      t0, 0(sp)           # T0 = function_ptr
        addi    sp, sp, 8           # bump SP past function_ptr
        jalr    t0                  # jump+link via T0; call function_ptr(A0=arg_ptr)

        # User function returned -> cleanly exit this thread
        li      a0, 0               # exit status = 0
        li      a7, 93              # __NR_exit (asm-generic)
        ecall                       # terminate this thread

        # ===== Parent path / error return =====
    1:
        sd      a0, -64(s0)         # result <- A0 (child TID or -errno)
    End Assembly

    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD LIFECYCLE
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_join" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until the target thread (identified by its TID
    handle) terminates. On Linux without pthread we use the FUTEX_WAIT
    protocol on the TID address -- the kernel atomically clears the
    CLONE_CHILD_CLEARTID address when the thread exits, which wakes any
    futex waiters. For this minimal implementation we wait on the TID itself
    as the futex address with expected value = handle; the kernel zeroes
    it on thread exit, satisfying the wake condition.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Issue futex(addr=handle, op=FUTEX_WAIT (0), val=0, timeout=NULL) via the
    platform-routed syscall_4 dispatcher with syscall number = __NR_futex
    (98 on rv64, asm-generic). The kernel returns 0 when woken by
    exit-cleartid, or -EAGAIN if the value has already changed (thread
    already exited). Either outcome is a successful join.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure kernel-blocking call; the thread descheduled until the kernel wakes
    it on target-thread exit. No spin, no userspace polling.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The handle must be a TID owned by the same thread-group as the caller
    (the kernel rejects futex addresses outside the process's address space
    with -EFAULT).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let futex_wait be 0
    Let timeout_ptr be 0
    Return proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wait, 0, timeout_ptr
End Process

Process called "thread_detach" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    On Linux the kernel auto-reaps a thread once it exits and no joiner is
    waiting; there is no separate detach syscall (unlike Solaris/Windows).
    The function exists for ABI symmetry with platforms that DO require a
    detach call; on Linux it is a true no-op.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 1 to signal "successfully detached" without invoking the kernel.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero-cost (one register load, one return).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition; no permission considerations.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "thread_exit" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Terminate the calling thread immediately with the supplied exit_code.
    Uses __NR_exit (93 on rv64, asm-generic) -- the per-thread exit,
    NOT __NR_exit_group (94) which would terminate the whole process.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through the syscall_exit dispatcher which on rv64 invokes
    __NR_exit (93) via `ecall`.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall; this function never returns.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the calling thread; other threads in the thread-group
    continue running.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_exit from Syscall with exit_code
End Process

Process called "thread_current_id" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the kernel TID of the calling thread (distinct from PID in
    multi-threaded processes). On rv64 this is the gettid syscall = 178
    (asm-generic numbering; x86_64 uses 186).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_0(178). The kernel returns the TID in A0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall, no arguments; ~50 ns on modern hardware.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No permission requirements; TID is always observable by the thread itself.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_0 from Syscall with 178
End Process

Process called "thread_yield" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Voluntarily yield the CPU to the scheduler. Useful for cooperative
    spin-loops and busy-wait fallback paths. Linux rv64 syscall =
    __NR_sched_yield = 124.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_0(124). Kernel returns 0 unconditionally on
    success; we forward that.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Triggers a scheduler invocation; cheap if no contention, expensive
    (microseconds) under load. Prefer futex_wait for real blocking.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the caller's scheduling state; no privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_0 from Syscall with 124
End Process

Process called "thread_sleep" takes microseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sleep the calling thread for the requested duration (microseconds).
    Implemented via nanosleep (__NR_nanosleep = 101 on rv64); takes a
    timespec { tv_sec, tv_nsec } pointer. We convert microseconds to that
    split-form before issuing the syscall.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Decompose microseconds into seconds + remainder.
    2. Multiply remainder by 1000 to get nanoseconds.
    3. mmap a 16-byte region for the timespec struct (tv_sec at +0,
       tv_nsec at +8, both int64).
    4. Write the fields via memory_set_int64.
    5. Invoke syscall_2(101, timespec_ptr, NULL_remainder_ptr).
    6. Unmap the timespec region.
    7. Return the syscall result (0 on full sleep, -EINTR if interrupted).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    mmap+munmap overhead is ~2 syscalls beyond the nanosleep itself. For
    high-frequency micro-sleeps consider a stack-allocated timespec, but
    on rv64 we do not yet have stack-buffer primitives in the Runa
    intrinsics -- heap is the safe path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No special privileges; nanosleep is unrestricted. The mmap is
    PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, so the timespec is
    not visible to other processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seconds be microseconds divided by 1000000
    Let remaining_us be microseconds modulo by 1000000
    Let nanoseconds be remaining_us multiplied by 1000

    Note: Allocate timespec (16 bytes: tv_sec int64, tv_nsec int64).
    Let timespec_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If timespec_ptr is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timespec_ptr, 0, seconds
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timespec_ptr, 8, nanoseconds

    Note: nanosleep(timespec_ptr, NULL remainder_ptr).
    Let result be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with 101, timespec_ptr, 0

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with timespec_ptr, 16

    Return result
End Process

Process called "thread_set_name" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Set a human-readable name for the calling thread (visible in
    /proc/<tid>/comm and via gdb/perf). Uses prctl(PR_SET_NAME = 15,
    name_ptr) via __NR_prctl (167 on rv64).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_2(167, 15, name_ptr). name_ptr must point to a
    null-terminated string of at most 16 bytes (kernel-enforced).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One-time setup cost (~100 ns); the name persists for the thread's
    lifetime. No effect on hot-path performance.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The caller can only name its own thread (PR_SET_NAME applies to
    current thread).
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_2 from Syscall with 167, 15, name
End Process

Process called "thread_get_name" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux exposes thread names via /proc/<tid>/comm and prctl(PR_GET_NAME),
    but the latter requires a caller-supplied buffer. To preserve the
    33-proc dispatcher signature (returns Integer, no out-parameter), this
    implementation returns 0 as a sentinel meaning "not retrieved here".
    Callers who need the name should open /proc/self/task/<tid>/comm
    directly via syscall_open + syscall_read.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 0 unconditionally -- the contract has no buffer slot to write
    into; promoting this to an out-param requires changing the dispatcher
    ABI across all 18 platforms, which is out of scope for this primitive.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero cost; no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
MUTEX (futex-backed)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "mutex_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte futex word (initialized to 0 = unlocked) via mmap.
    The mutex handle is the futex word's address. All mutex operations
    are pure userspace until contention is detected, at which point
    FUTEX_WAIT/FUTEX_WAKE descend into the kernel.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS; on
    failure return 0 (caller treats 0 as null-handle). Write 0 to the
    word to ensure deterministic unlocked state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap call per mutex -- coarse. Callers creating many mutexes
    should batch into an arena; this primitive optimizes for correctness
    over allocator throughput.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mapping is process-private (MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS) -- no
    cross-process leakage of the futex word.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let futex_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If futex_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with futex_word, 0, 0
    Return futex_word
End Process

Process called "mutex_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the 4-byte futex-word mapping. Callers MUST ensure no other
    thread holds or is waiting on the mutex -- destroying a held futex
    is a use-after-free hazard.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4) via the platform-routed dispatcher.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must own the mapping (mmap-returned addresses are private).
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "mutex_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire the mutex via a CAS-first / futex-wait-fallback protocol:
      1. Fast path: atomic CAS(handle, expected=0, desired=1). If the word
         was unlocked (0), we now hold it (1) and return immediately --
         no kernel transition.
      2. Slow path: word was nonzero (held by another thread). Spin-load
         the word; on each observation that it is 0 retry the CAS. If the
         word is still nonzero, issue FUTEX_WAIT (op = 128 = FUTEX_WAIT |
         FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG) with expected = 1. The kernel parks the
         caller until mutex_unlock issues FUTEX_WAKE.

    FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG (= 128) tells the kernel the futex is process-local,
    enabling a faster wake path that skips inode-based identification.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-phase loop matching the arm64 sibling exactly. The atomic_*
    operations bottom out at RISC-V LR.W/SC.W (load-reserved /
    store-conditional, "A" extension) inside atomic_core; the futex
    syscall number is __NR_futex = 98 on rv64.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended acquire: ~3 instructions (1 CAS + 1 branch + 1 return).
    Contended path: 1 syscall per wakeup; the kernel batches wakes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex (FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG) -- no cross-process
    contention or signaling.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Fast path
    Let expected be 0
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, expected, 1
    If success is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Slow path: FUTEX_WAIT | FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG = 128.
    Let futex_wait be 128
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is equal to 0:
            Set success to proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, 1
            If success is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wait, 1, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the mutex (clear the futex word to 0) and wake one waiter.
    The release barrier (memory_barrier_release) ensures all prior writes
    by the unlocking thread are visible to the next acquirer before the
    word goes to 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. memory_set_int32(handle, 0, 0) -- release the word.
    2. memory_barrier_release -- RISC-V `fence rw, w` inside atomic_core.
    3. syscall_3(98, handle, FUTEX_WAKE | FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG = 129, 1)
       -- wake exactly one waiter (val = 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Issues an unconditional FUTEX_WAKE syscall (Linux generic sysnum 98)
    on every release; the kernel returns zero work when the wait queue is
    empty. Per-call cost is dominated by the user-to-kernel transition
    (ecall instruction plus the RV64 LP64 ABI register save), so the
    unconditional path keeps the release sequence branch-free.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex; no cross-process effect.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with handle, 0, 0
    proc memory_barrier_release from Atomic

    Let futex_wake be 129
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wake, 1

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_try_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking acquire: attempt the CAS once; return success/failure
    without spinning or syscalling. Used by lock-elision and try-acquire
    patterns.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single atomic_compare_and_swap(handle, 0, 1); return its result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only; no kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let expected be 0
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, expected, 1
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SEMAPHORE (futex-backed counting semaphore)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "semaphore_create" takes initial_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte counter word initialized to initial_count. The word
    doubles as a futex address for blocking waiters when the counter
    reaches 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS); on
    failure return 0. Initialize the word to initial_count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per semaphore; consider arena-pooling for bulk usage.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sem_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If sem_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with sem_word, 0, initial_count
    Return sem_word
End Process

Process called "semaphore_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the counter mapping. Caller must ensure no thread is parked
    on the semaphore via FUTEX_WAIT.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "semaphore_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically decrement the counter; if the pre-decrement value was > 0
    the wait succeeded immediately. Otherwise restore the counter and
    park on the futex via FUTEX_WAIT.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Loop:
      1. Load current counter.
      2. If > 0: atomic_fetch_add(handle, -1); if pre-value > 0 we succeeded.
         If a race made pre-value <= 0, restore via atomic_fetch_add(+1).
      3. Else: FUTEX_WAIT(handle, FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG, 0, NULL).
      4. Loop.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: 2 atomics + 1 load. Contended: 1 syscall per wake.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex.
    @End Security_Scope

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is greater than 0:
            Let new_val be current minus 1
            Let old_val be proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
            If old_val is greater than 0:
                Return 1
            End If
            proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1
        End If

        proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, handle, 128, 0, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Increment the counter and wake one waiter. The increment is atomic
    so concurrent signals do not lose counts.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1).
    2. syscall_3(98, handle, FUTEX_WAKE | FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG = 129, 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always wakes; no "has_waiters" gating (see mutex_unlock comment).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let futex_wake be 129
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wake, 1

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_try_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking variant of semaphore_wait: attempt the decrement once
    without descending into the kernel. Returns 1 on success, 0 if the
    counter is at 0 (would block).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Snapshot the counter; if > 0 attempt atomic_fetch_add(-1). On lost
    race (pre-value <= 0), restore via +1 and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only; no kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is greater than 0:
        Let old_val be proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
        If old_val is greater than 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
CONDITION VARIABLE (sequence-numbered futex)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "condvar_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte sequence word (initialized to 0). The word is
    bumped on every signal/broadcast; waiters check the pre-wait value
    via FUTEX_WAIT-with-expected, which atomically blocks only if the
    sequence has not changed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes; init word to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per condvar; pool with arena for bulk use.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cv_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If cv_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with cv_word, 0, 0
    Return cv_word
End Process

Process called "condvar_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the sequence-word mapping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "condvar_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically release the associated mutex and block on the condition
    variable's sequence. Re-acquire the mutex before returning. The
    "atomicity" of release+wait is achieved by the FUTEX_WAIT_PRIVATE
    expected-value check: if a signal raced in between unlock and wait,
    the sequence will have advanced and futex returns EAGAIN immediately
    without sleeping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot the sequence number from the cv word.
    2. mutex_unlock(mutex_handle).
    3. syscall_4(98, cv_handle, FUTEX_WAIT_PRIVATE (128), expected = seq,
       NULL timeout).
    4. mutex_lock(mutex_handle) -- reacquire on wakeup.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worst case: 2 syscalls (unlock-wake + wait) + 1 atomic reacquire.
    Best case (spurious wake): 1 syscall + 1 reacquire.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Both futexes are process-private. The mutex must be held by the
    caller on entry (verified by mutex_unlock semantics).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seq be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with cv_handle, 0

    mutex_unlock(mutex_handle)

    proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, cv_handle, 128, seq, 0

    mutex_lock(mutex_handle)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_timed_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer, timeout_us as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bounded variant of condvar_wait: the futex returns -ETIMEDOUT if the
    timeout expires before a signal. The timeout is supplied as a
    timespec struct (sec + nsec) pointer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot sequence.
    2. mutex_unlock.
    3. Decompose timeout_us into sec + nsec; mmap a 16-byte timespec;
       write the fields.
    4. FUTEX_WAIT(cv_handle, FUTEX_PRIVATE 128, seq, timespec_ptr).
    5. munmap the timespec.
    6. mutex_lock.

    If the timespec mmap fails we skip the wait altogether (degraded but
    safe -- caller treats this as immediate timeout). The mutex is still
    reacquired so the caller's invariant holds.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two extra syscalls (mmap + munmap) compared to condvar_wait. For
    tight loops with frequent timed waits consider preallocating a
    per-thread timespec scratch buffer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex; timespec mapping is MAP_PRIVATE.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seq be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with cv_handle, 0

    mutex_unlock(mutex_handle)

    Let seconds be timeout_us divided by 1000000
    Let remaining_us be timeout_us modulo by 1000000
    Let nanoseconds be remaining_us multiplied by 1000

    Let timespec_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If timespec_ptr is greater than or equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timespec_ptr, 0, seconds
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timespec_ptr, 8, nanoseconds

        Let result be proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, cv_handle, 128, seq, timespec_ptr

        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with timespec_ptr, 16
    End If

    mutex_lock(mutex_handle)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake exactly one waiter blocked on the condvar. The sequence is
    bumped first so any in-flight wait sees a stale expected value and
    returns -EAGAIN.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1) -- advance sequence.
    2. FUTEX_WAKE(handle, FUTEX_PRIVATE 129, 1) -- wake one.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always issues the wake syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let futex_wake be 129
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wake, 1

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_broadcast" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake all waiters blocked on the condvar (vs condvar_signal's single
    wake). Used when the predicate change affects all waiters
    simultaneously.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1) -- advance sequence.
    2. FUTEX_WAKE(handle, FUTEX_PRIVATE 129, INT_MAX = 2147483647).
       INT_MAX in the val slot means "wake every parked waiter".
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall regardless of waiter count.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex; the kernel only wakes threads in the caller's
    process.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let futex_wake be 129
    Let int_max be 2147483647
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wake, int_max

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
READ-WRITE LOCK (single 32-bit word, MSB=writer, low bits=reader count)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "rwlock_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte state word. Encoding:
      bit 31      = 1 if a writer holds the lock (value is negative as
                    signed int32)
      bits 0..30 = number of readers currently holding the lock
    Initialized to 0 (no readers, no writer).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes; init to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per rwlock.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let rwlock_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If rwlock_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with rwlock_word, 0, 0
    Return rwlock_word
End Process

Process called "rwlock_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the state-word mapping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "rwlock_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire a shared (reader) lock. Spin-and-wait protocol:
      1. Snapshot the state word.
      2. If negative (writer holds it): FUTEX_WAIT until state changes.
      3. Otherwise: attempt CAS(state, state+1). If lost race, retry.
    Multiple readers may hold the lock simultaneously (count increments).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Standard ticket-less reader entry loop. The FUTEX_WAIT uses the
    full state word as expected -- if any change (writer release, new
    reader) occurs, the wait returns and we retry.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: 1 load + 1 CAS = ~5 ns.
    Writer-blocked: kernel block via FUTEX_WAIT.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex.
    @End Security_Scope

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is less than 0:
            proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, handle, 128, current, 0
        Otherwise:
            Let new_val be current plus 1
            Let old_val be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, current, new_val
            If old_val is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire an exclusive (writer) lock. Writers wait for the state word
    to reach 0 (no readers, no writer), then CAS it to MIN_INT32
    (0x80000000) to claim sole ownership.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Spin loop:
      1. Snapshot state.
      2. If 0: attempt CAS(state, 0, MIN_INT32). On success: hold the lock.
      3. Otherwise: FUTEX_WAIT(state).
    MIN_INT32 (-2147483648, hex 0x80000000) is chosen so the state word's
    sign bit (bit 31) is set when a writer holds it; reader code tests
    for "current < 0" to detect writer presence.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended write-lock acquire: 1 load + 1 CAS.
    Contended: O(N) syscalls in worst case (each reader/writer release
    wakes the writer for re-evaluation).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let write_bit be -2147483648

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is equal to 0:
            Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, write_bit
            If success is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 98, handle, 128, current, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release whichever lock mode is held. If the state word is negative
    (writer held), clear it to 0 -- the writer's exit unblocks the entire
    population. Otherwise (reader held), atomically decrement the reader
    count. Always wake all waiters so any blocked writer can re-evaluate.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot current state.
    2. If < 0: write 0 (clear writer flag).
       Else: atomic_fetch_add(handle, -1) -- decrement reader count.
    3. memory_barrier_release.
    4. FUTEX_WAKE(handle, FUTEX_PRIVATE 129, INT_MAX) -- wake everyone.

    The "wake all" choice (vs wake-one) is correct because a single
    writer-release may unblock multiple readers; a single reader-release
    may unblock a writer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always issues a wake syscall. Optimization opportunity: track waiter
    count to skip wake when no one is parked (deferred).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private futex.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with handle, 0, 0
    Otherwise:
        proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
    End If

    proc memory_barrier_release from Atomic

    Let futex_wake be 129
    Let int_max be 2147483647
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 98, handle, futex_wake, int_max

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking reader acquisition: snapshot the state; if a writer
    holds it (state < 0) fail immediately; otherwise attempt the
    single-shot CAS increment.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Snapshot + branch + CAS; no syscall.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let new_val be current plus 1
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, current, new_val
    Return success
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking writer acquisition: single CAS from 0 to MIN_INT32.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    One CAS; return its result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let write_bit be -2147483648
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, write_bit
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Hardware Query - CPU Affinity-Based Concurrency Detection
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "hardware_concurrency" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the number of CPU cores available to the calling process.
    Uses sched_getaffinity(pid=0, cpusetsize=128, mask) -- fills a 1024-bit
    affinity mask, one bit per logical CPU the process may run on. We
    popcount the mask byte-by-byte via Kernighan's bit-clear trick.
    On any syscall failure we return 1 (never 0; callers expect a
    positive worker count and would divide-by-zero or spawn no threads
    otherwise).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap 128 bytes for the mask (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
       MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS).
    2. Zero the buffer (defensive -- the kernel only writes the bytes
       it uses, so uninitialized trailing bytes would inflate the
       popcount).
    3. syscall_3(__NR_sched_getaffinity = 123, pid=0, cpusetsize=128,
       mask_ptr). Returns bytes written on success, -errno on failure.
    4. Popcount the written bytes: for each byte b, while b != 0,
       b = b & (b - 1); total_set += 1.
    5. munmap the buffer.
    6. Return max(total_set, 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap + one syscall + one munmap; popcount loop is O(bytes_written
    * popcount_per_byte) which is at most 128 * 8 = 1024 iterations.
    Result is typically cached by the runtime, so the cost is amortized
    across the process lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    sched_getaffinity is unrestricted for pid=0 (self). The mmap is
    process-private. No information leaks across processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask_buf be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 128, 3, 34, -1, 0
    If mask_buf is less than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Zero the buffer
    Let zero_idx be 0
    While zero_idx is less than 128:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with mask_buf, zero_idx, 0
        Set zero_idx to zero_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: sched_getaffinity syscall on rv64 = 123 (asm-generic).
    Let written be proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 123, 0, 128, mask_buf
    If written is less than or equal to 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with mask_buf, 128
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Popcount over the bytes the kernel actually wrote.
    Let total_set be 0
    Let byte_idx be 0
    While byte_idx is less than written:
        Let byte_val be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with mask_buf, byte_idx
        While byte_val is not equal to 0:
            Let lowered be byte_val minus 1
            Set byte_val to byte_val bitwise and lowered
            Set total_set to total_set plus 1
        End While
        Set byte_idx to byte_idx plus 1
    End While

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with mask_buf, 128

    If total_set is less than 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return total_set
End Process
